{{refimprove|date=May 2013}} [[Image:IHES main building.jpg|thumbnail|IHÉS main building]]
The '''Institut des hautes études scientifiques''' ('''IHÉS'''; English: Institute of Advanced Scientific Studies) is a [[France|French]] institute supporting advanced research in [[mathematics]] and [[theoretical physics]]. It is located in [[Bures-sur-Yvette]] just south of [[Paris]]. It is now part of the federal [[University of Paris-Saclay]] as an advanced studies institute.
==History== The IHÉS, was founded in 1958 by businessman and mathematical physicist [[Léon Motchane]] with the help of [[Robert Oppenheimer]] and [[Jean Dieudonné]] as a research centre in France, modeled on the renowned [[Institute for Advanced Study]] in Princeton, United States.<ref name="50th anniversary">{{cite web |title=On the occasion of receiving the Seki Takakazu Prize |url=http://mathsoc.jp/publication/tushin/1203/IHES12-3.pdf |publisher=[[Mathematical Society of Japan]]}}</ref>
{{quotation|[[IHÉS]] explicitly draws inspiration from the model of the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton (IAS). ... IHÉS adopted its basic characteristics - the intellectual ones - as a high level institute dedicated to basic research - and certain practical ones - such as the tradition of tea being served daily, conducive to exchanges of views. Of equal importance was the relationship between Oppenheimer and Léon Motchane (1900-1990), the founder and first director of IHÉS. As life member of the scientific committee, advisor to the director, frequent visitor and regular correspondent, Oppenheimer played a major role in the crucial early years at IHÉS. ... Oppenheimer and Motchane ... exchanged long letters and short telegrams on all aspects of life at IHÉS. ... Visits by Oppenheimer were cleverly orchestrated by Léon Motchane and reported in the press. Oppenheimer’s presence was an event in itself and his coming to lHÉS gave the Institute important official recognition. Oppenheimer was to come to IHÉS three times: from 16 to 19 September 1959, on 17 and 18 October 1961 (in Bures, although the Institute had not moved there yet), and from 14 to 17 May 1963. His last visit, planned for 1965, was cancelled for health reasons.<ref>[http://www.ihes.fr/jsp/site/Portal.jsp?document_id=3810&portlet_id=1026 IHES – Oppenheimer and IHÉS (1958-1967)]</ref>}}
The strong personality of [[Alexandre Grothendieck]] and the broad sweep of his revolutionizing theories were a dominating feature of the first ten years at the IHÉS.{{citation needed|date=February 2012}} [[René Thom]] received an invitation from IHÉS in 1963 and after his appointment remained there until his death in 2002.<ref>{{cite book |last=edited by Lawrence D. Kritzman, Brian J. Reilly |title=The Columbia History Of Twentieth-Century French Thought |publisher=[[Columbia University Press]] |page=665}}</ref> [[Dennis Sullivan]] is remembered as one who had a special talent for encouraging fruitful exchanges among visitors and provoking a new and deeper insight into their ideas.{{citation needed|date=February 2012}}
The IHÉS runs a highly regarded mathematical journal, ''[[Publications Mathématiques de l'IHÉS]]''.
IHÉS celebrated its 50th anniversary in 2008<ref name="50th anniversary" /><ref>{{cite web |last=Jackson |first=Allyn |title=Grothendieck at 80, IHES at 50 |url=http://www.ams.org/notices/200808/tx080800962p.pdf |publisher=[[American Mathematical Society]] |accessdate=2008}}</ref> and the 40th anniversary in 1998.<ref>{{cite web |last=Jackson |first=Allyn |title=The IHÉS at Forty |url=http://www.ams.org/notices/199903/ihes-changes.pdf |publisher=[[American Mathematical Society]] |accessdate=March 1999}}</ref>
